1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,120
Correct. Well, it seems that this data can be nicely separated by a line,

2

00:00:04,120  -->  00:00:05,500
which is this line over here,

3

00:00:05,500  -->  00:00:08,580
and it seems that most students over the line get

4

00:00:08,580  -->  00:00:12,220
accepted and most students under the line get rejected.

5

00:00:12,220  -->  00:00:15,175
This line is going to be our model.

6

00:00:15,175  -->  00:00:18,280
The model makes a couple of mistakes since there are

7

00:00:18,280  -->  00:00:22,000
a few blue points that are under the line and a few red points over the line.

8

00:00:22,000  -->  00:00:23,960
But we're not going to care about those.

9

00:00:23,960  -->  00:00:28,180
We'll say that it's safe to predict that if a point is over the line,

10

00:00:28,180  -->  00:00:29,680
the student gets accepted,

11

00:00:29,680  -->  00:00:31,260
and if it's under the line,

12

00:00:31,260  -->  00:00:33,260
then the student gets rejected.

13

00:00:33,260  -->  00:00:36,420
Based on this model, we look at the new student and we see that

14

00:00:36,420  -->  00:00:39,560
they're over here at the 0.76, which is above the line.

15

00:00:39,560  -->  00:00:43,060
We can assume with some confidence that the student gets accepted.

16

00:00:43,060  -->  00:00:46,455
If you answer, yes, that's the correct answer.

17

00:00:46,455  -->  00:00:48,660
Now a question arises.

18

00:00:48,660  -->  00:00:51,600
The question is, how do we find this line?

19

00:00:51,600  -->  00:00:53,400
We can eyeball it,

20

00:00:53,400  -->  00:00:54,940
but the computer can't.

21

00:00:54,940  -->  00:00:59,720
We'll dedicate the rest of the section to show you algorithms that will find this line,

22

00:00:59,720  -->  00:01:01,140
not only for this example,

23

00:01:01,140  -->  00:01:04,560
but for much more general and complicated cases.
